sublevels.theory:
**Access specifiers** control member visibility:
- `public` — accessible from anywhere
- `private` — only accessible from within the class and friend functions
- `protected` — accessible from within the class and derived classes

Getters and setters let you safely expose private data:
```cpp
class Circle {
private:
    double radius;
public:
    void setRadius(double r) { if (r >= 0) radius = r; }
    double getRadius() const { return radius; }
    double getArea() const { return 3.14159 * radius * radius; }
};
```

The **scope resolution operator** `::` defines member functions outside the class.

**`const` member functions** promise not to modify the object:
```cpp
double getArea() const { return 3.14 * radius * radius; }
```

**`mutable`** — allows a specific member to be modified even inside a `const` function:
`mutable int callCount = 0;`

**Friend functions/classes:** can access private members:
```cpp
class Box {
    friend void printVolume(Box& b);
private:
    int volume;
};
void printVolume(Box& b) { std::cout << b.volume; }
```

**Operator member overloads:** `operator+`, `operator[]`, `operator()` are often member functions.

**`[[nodiscard]]` (C++17/20):** on methods to warn if return is silently dropped.

**Ref-qualified member functions (C++11):**
```cpp
class Str {
    std::string data;
public:
    std::string& get() &  { return data; }      // lvalue object
    std::string  get() && { return std::move(data); } // rvalue object
};
```

**Concept-constrained member functions (C++20):** `template<typename T> requires std::integral<T> void set(T v);`

**`protected` inheritance:** the public members of the base become protected in the derived — rarely used.
